Here is the info. This is a long post but it covers more then just debuffs but this is information that should never be lost.<br>
<br>
Thank you Lotusfly (again I might add)<br>
<br>
- Endalin<br>
<br>
Chaps, I am, quite frankly, amazed. It seems to me that I'm playing a slightly different class to some of the posters here, at least from personal experience. The amount of incorrect information represented here as fact is a little worrying; I've been reading down the posts thinking &quot;Good lord&quot; and &quot;Wherever does that idea come from?&quot; and so forth. Let me do as I can to respond to some of you. I must admit to being puzzled at some of the responses, but perhaps we can iron this out to some satisfaction. <br>
<br>
I'd like you guys to be happy, and I want you to share a little of the feeling that I, and my druids, feel when we're smacking the baddies of Norrath.<br>
<br>
I think what would be most productive of all in trying to communicate this would be to give you some case studies. I see a lot of confusion in the above posts, perhaps this will give you a little glimpse into the way in which druids are useful. To quote a senior member of development staff, &quot;I like the way druids turned out, if I were levelling another class to 60 I'd make it a druid&quot;. I can't help but agree; maybe these case studies will help express my opinion.<br>
<br>
As a little background, these are case studies from the &quot;uber&quot; guild of our server, much as I dislike the word. With the new expansion, our druids are a big asset and something that I wouldn't like to be without. From these studies I hope to show you that at the very pinnacle of the end-game, even then druids are a great addition to the raid force. <br>
<br>
This is a long post, some people will not want to read it - that's fine. It's long because I care about the class, and I care about you all enjoying it even just a fraction as much as I do. <br>
<br>
<br>
1. The Temple of Ssraeshza.<br>
<br>
This is a great zone for druids, and one of the focal raid points of the new expansion. Mobs here have an enormous Ac, so much so that the melee classes are constantly saying how little fun it is hitting for 1, 1, 1, 5.<br>
<br>
Let's take the Creator as an example. He's a massive fight, and exhibits the usual traits of Ssra fights: high ac, high HP, AEs with a curse that makes all heals on you only heal for 20% of normal, and AEs for damage too.<br>
<br>
During this fight, melees are suffering because of the high Ac. The main tank is suffering because of the &quot;Balance of Zebuxoruk&quot; curse - every CH that lands on them is only healing 2k HP, every DL that lands on them is healing about 200HP. Everyone is suffering from the HP drain, HP bars are slowly and steadily falling all around. The fight lasts for some 15 minutes, so this is a problem. It's generally a hard place to be.<br>
<br>
Most clerical mana is tied up with the main tank. The rest of the raid force is scrounging heals from shamen and druids. As tanks fall, the shamen (a notoriously unpopular class across all servers, averaging 1-3 per uber guild) are rebuffing them, whilst trying to keep the Creator slowed and crippled. They don't have a great deal of mana for heals, but sometimes they can squeeze out a Torpor on a lucky caster.<br>
<br>
Druids do a lot during this fight, I'll cover some further points in a moment - for now let's look at the healing.<br>
<br>
It's the druids that are keeping alive a large portion of the raid force for this encounter. We're not main healers, we can't effectively keep someone alive that's tanking a 500+ hitting mob, nor were we intended to. Thankfully, 90% of the raid force are not tanking, and that's where we come in.<br>
<br>
HPs are dropping all around; I usually have druids healing a collection of rogues, casters, hybrids as most guilds do. During this time, the druid is dealing with HP bars that are falling over 15 minutes. They are spending their mana on Chloro/NT and keeping their group alive. They do a good job currently; with Flowing Thought and Mental Clarity, Healing Adept/Gift and good, plain mana management, our druids can cope. <br>
<br>
Of course we have the full range of druids - from those with a lot of time to get exp with all of the above boons, to those who can't play as much as they'd like and so have lesser attributes. All cope well with the task of keeping their group alive in a painful AE. Those with better attributes get to do more, which I'll come to. <br>
<br>
During this time, as in a lot of fights across Norrath, the AE is slowly eating your group over an extended period of time - extended because the mob has a serious amount of HPs, as is common at this point in the game.<br>
<br>
Rather than spending mana on NT and Chloro, our druids will be using Nature's Recovery as much as they can to save mana (once it stacks with regrowth). At this stage of the game, I trust that our druids can judge when a player has taken 900 HP of damage. <br>
<br>
This fight is not unique. Most encounters, a druid will be grouped with people that have taken 900HP of damage, or can anticipate that they will take 900HP of damage. My druids will get 100% healing utilisation out of Nature's Recovery nearly every time that they cast it, because they know from experience where the heals are needed. Every time they do cast it, they're saving mana. <br>
<br>
An above poster seemed to imply that it was difficult to judge the group's HPs, and that getting maximum utilisation out of NR would be a difficult thing to do. I don't agree with that; even the druid with the most humble skills on my raids can get 100% utilisation from this spell.<br>
<br>
Across this Creator fight, they will be saving 150mana every 1.5 mins, or 1500 mana across the total 15 minute encounter. Each and every druid will have 1-2 bubbles of extra mana to use, simply because of this new spell. <br>
<br>
Yes, you're don't have Torpor. The shamen have bigger fish to fry, on the whole, than watching group HPs. Across most encounters that I watch on various servers, the shamen have their attention elsewhere. They have an efficient heal-over-time heal, but by no means is it making the druid redundant on raids. The druids are contributing 100% and without them a large number of the raid force would be languishing at their bind points.<br>
<br>
That's the druid exercising the healing portion of their class on raids. We're not all-out fully-specialised healers (clerics), and so we don't do it as well as them. However, we do have a massive and pronounced effect on the raid.<br>
<br>
Let's move on to looking at how the druid exercises the other portions of their class skills on the raid. Whilst the cleric is healing 100%, the druid gets to do some other things - that's the trade off. I wouldn't want to be a cleric, it would drive me mad. Most clerics that I talk to find their class unsatisfying as they have been reduced to a simple button-pushing mechanism when their spot on the CH rotation comes around.<br>
<br>
Before we go into a major fight like the Creator, I like to have a bit of fun. I call a &quot;druid huddle&quot;, and all the druids form into one group temporarily, form a little circle and crouch, as in a little huddle in American Football. <br>
<br>
Here, we have a bit of fun. We have five debuffs, all of which need to be cast, and in a specific order. These debuffs make a big difference, which I'll cover in a moment. Depending on the number of druids on the raid, and what other tasks they have, we split the tasks accordingly. The tasks are split to share the mana load (some of the following are real mana drains to keep up over 15 minutes) and to share the agro load (some of the following will get you killed if one druid tries to keep to many up for 15 minutes).<br>
<br>
i. Sunder in first - thanks to its &quot;lurish&quot; resistance check, this spell will land the easiest and, after malo, makes the rest of our debuffs land nicely. An early cast, this is agrolicious.<br>
<br>
ii. Fixation in second - and down goes the mob's ATK by 60, and its ac by 18. This is a low maintenance debuff, the druid will only need to refresh it once during the fight - but it is vital that it is refreshed *before it fades*, otherwise it won't stick.<br>
<br>
iii. Disjunction in third - and this is the reason it won't stick if it is allowed to fade. Disjunction will overwrite Sunder, and leave Fixation, for a massive ATK debuff total of 120. I'll run some logs of a creature with and without the 120 ATK debuff on it, and you can see the damage output difference vs. a main tank. The Ac of the mob has gone down a further 27, on top of Fixation's 18, also.<br>
<br>
iv. and v. Breath of Ro and Immolate - Breath is a big mana drain for 15 minutes and is high agro over that time. The druid that keeps this up needs to have their other duties as low-agro and low-mana load; typically, if a druid has a cleric in their group they'll be getting Breath duty. Breath drives down the FR of the mob by a further 31, and takes a big 21ac chunk out of it. Immolate is less strenuous in terms of agro and mana, but requiries a lot of recasting - and it takes a further 18ac chunk.<br>
<br>
Once the druids have gone to work, the mob is suffering from:<br>
<br>
- 84 ac reduction. On all mobs, reducing the ac by this much (no other class can come close to such a reduction) causes a satisfying jump in melee damage from your 30 or so melees that are swinging away on the mob. Throw in a shamanic Cripple (-33ac), a necro's group AC tap (1 etc., and the mob is suffering from heightened raid melee, mostly thanks to the druids.<br>
<br>
It brings a smile to my face when our main tanks and rogues are shouting &quot;Is the AC down?&quot; in guild, and the druids can say &quot;Yes!&quot;. We're effectively buffing the melee output of the raid.<br>
<br>
- 98 FR reduction. This is pure evil. The battery of wizards are landing wave after wave of fire based nukes on the mob, magicians, druids and rangers are all getting massively reduced resists on their attacks and debuffs, and the necros are landing Funeral Pyre. This is something we're all accustomed to, to some degree, with Sunder (-42 FR) being so commonly used. With the full range of druid debuffs in, with coordination between the druids, the FR is down by over double that. It's just plain evil.<br>
<br>
- 120 ATK reduction. We've effectively knocked several levels off the mob in conventional melee terms. Versus a suitable main tank, the mob will hit less frequently, and for a lower amount of damage when he does so.<br>
<br>
And that's just the debuffing. Sunder, Fixation and Disjunction are low-maintenance. Breath and Immolate are heavy tasks. Remember that we've not counted the damage - over 15 minutes Breath will do 13.8k of damage, Immolate will do 3.6k. <br>
<br>
One druid will get Swarm duty (just over 20k of damage in 15 mins), one druid will optionally throw on a free Drones of Doom (5k over 15 mins). <br>
<br>
It is typical to give &quot;Remove Greater Curse&quot; scrolls to druids - they are a hugely rare spell. If you have one copy of this spell for your guild, as is likely, it will mean tying up on character 100% of the time casting it on the main tanks, curing the Balance of Zeb curse. Without this, the main tanks die fast. Shamen are in too short supply to spend one on curse curing, clerics are needed for their 100% heals - across most servers, Remove Greater Curse has gone to a druid. It's another duty for us, and without it the raid will (literally) be dead and be dead fast.<br>
<br>
Any druids with leftover mana we have throw in extra wildfires. Simply casting wildfire alone, a druid can do 1k of damage every 6 seconds - you can click a Shrunken Goblin Earring in between casts to remove the recast delay for back-to-back quick casts. That's a higher amount of damage than a rogue or a monk in an equivalent period (assuming 140 and 120 dps respectively for uber rogues and monks). Certainly, you have a mana and agro price to pay for such high damage, but my point is that you are making a real contribution to damage. That your nuke is has a smaller mana/damage ratio than a wizard nuke is no surprise and irrelevant - it amazes me how one can write off druid DDs when they can outdamage the guild's best equipped rogues should you wish to, over the period of time in which you cast them.<br>
<br>
After the duties are assigned, and the druids are excited, we dance a little, goof around, and then rejoin our groups and get to work.<br>
<br>
Druids are are a versatile class. We don't heal 100%, we do have a wonderful mix of decent healing, decent nukes, decent DoTs and excellent debuffs which specialise in an area no others do (Ac, Atk, FR).<br>
<br>
When the dust settles and we're awarding another FT6 shield to a lucky caster, the druids have their heads held up high and send me tells saying &quot;GD I love being a druid&quot; and &quot;Hell they've made us good now&quot;.<br>
<br>
I love it.<br>
<br>
That's to counter the &quot;Omg we suck on raids&quot;, &quot;Sigh... our nukes aren't so good&quot;, &quot;All I do on raids is regen and then pump 880 heals&quot; and so on. It's as good as you make it, and I wouldn't be without my core of druids for taking on the big mobs.<br>
<br>
As a subnote, I should answer &quot;Omg clerics have mass group buff now so no one needs potg, I'm useless&quot;. If you believe this, and if your guild casters, shamen and druids are using aegolism rather than PotG... I really don't know what to say to you.<br>
<br>
In my guild, the drill is as follows.<br>
<br>
The cleric will cast group aego on the whole raid, for 4 peridots - I love this! The peridot saving is enormous for us so far.<br>
<br>
I have a &quot;/gu Potg is in 5 mins, click off your aego if you need it&quot; which I then hit. Two mins later I hit my &quot;/gu Potg is in 3 mins, click off your aego if you need it&quot;. Finally, they get a &quot;/gu Potg is inc, click off your aego if you need it&quot; hotkey. This has to happen once every 2.5 hours (group aego's duration). It's not a big deal, and it helps me to gte our usually AFK casters to click their buff off. I then PotG all the mana users (less some clerics).<br>
<br>
PotG is 60 mana/minute, or 900 mana over a 15 minute Creator fight (for example). If your casters are using aego, I'd do something about it. <br>
<br>
Saving 900 mana per caster, assuming 20 casters... 18k mana regenned over a Creator fight which is being spent on other things: nukes, mod rods, CHs, DoTs, etc. Your guild needs to use PotG.<br>
<br>
That's the role of druids on my raids.<br>
<br>
<br>
2. Exp groups<br>
<br>
This one will be shorter, fear not. <br>
<br>
Currently, the exp spot of choice for most of us is dear old Howling Stones. I form a group here and get a yellow every 35 mins or so, it really is fast exp. When I'm forming the group I get the following:<br>
<br>
Group slot 1: Me (hehe)<br>
<br>
Group slot 2: Rogue #1 - luckily, my usual levelling partner and a Mrylokar's dagger user. <br>
<br>
Group slot 3: Tank, preferably a paladin. The group heals really work in the middle of a big train - Wave of Prexus keeps us all safe when we really need it, and it keeps the agro on the paladin.<br>
<br>
Group slot 4: Enchanter or bard. I prefer an enc, as it allows us to AE when we have mana. Bards can do this to a good extent with AE slow, but with an enchanter's AE stun and 75-mana AE mez you're best set.<br>
<br>
